onnect U.S. mosques to the Muslim world. By examining the tension between American Muslims’ ambivalence toward the American mainstream and their desire to enter it, Grewal puts contemporary debates about Islam in the context of a long history of American racial and religious exclusions. Probing the competing obligations of American Muslims to the nation and to the umma (the global community of Muslim believers), Islam is a Foreign Country investigates the meaning of American citizenship and the place of Islam in a global age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIslamxUnited States. 0aIslamzUnited States. 0aMuslim youthxAttitudesxUnited States. 0aMuslim youthxReligious lifexUnited States. 0aMuslim youthxReligious lifezUnited States. 0aMuslim youthzUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aSocial integrationxUnited States. 0aSocial integrationzUnited States. 0aUmmah (Islam). 0aUnited StatesxEthnic relations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978147980088940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479800193.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479800193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479800193/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK